Using the Intel RealSense ZR300  that has the "motion module" with fish_eye camera.  Accessing the fish_eye stream and getting the intrinsic and distortion parameters is supported by the current librealsense.   Additionally there is a sample displaying these newly available streams.  

However, there is no documentations on specifically what the fisheye intrinsic parameters mean.   At minimum, if the equations were simply added to the function rs_project_point_to_pixel().  Currently the function asserts when provided intrinsics returned from the api.

```
  auto intrinsics = dcam.dev->get_stream_intrinsics(rs::stream::fisheye);
  auto p = intrinsics.project(rs::float3{ my_x, my_y, my_z });   // this will assert!!!!!
```


We tried an radial projection with distortion implementation and a few variants based on common conventions that people tend to use (there are a number of them), but in our tests things didn't quite line up.  Consequently, not sure if equation is correct, or if the calibration parameters are off.  code tested is:
```
static void rs_project_point_to_pixel(float pixel[2], const struct rs_intrinsics * intrin, const float point[3])
{
    assert(intrin->model != RS_DISTORTION_INVERSE_BROWN_CONRADY); // Cannot project to an inverse-distorted image
    // comment out the assert for FTHETA:
    //assert(intrin->model != RS_DISTORTION_FTHETA); // Cannot project to an ftheta image

    float x = point[0] / point[2], y = point[1] / point[2];

    if(intrin->model == RS_DISTORTION_MODIFIED_BROWN_CONRADY) 
    {
        .... same as before ...  
    }
    if (intrin->model == RS_DISTORTION_FTHETA)
    {
		float r2 = x*x + y*y;
		float r = sqrt(x*x + y*y);
		float t = atan(r);
		float f = 1 + intrin->coeffs[0] * t*t;    // we noticed other coeffs, besides coeffs[0], were all 0.0 anyways
		x *= f;
		y *= f;
		if (r>1e-8)
		{
			x *= t / r;
			y *= t / r;
		}
    }
    pixel[0] = x * intrin->fx + intrin->ppx;
    pixel[1] = y * intrin->fy + intrin->ppy;
}
```
Note, the above code may be incorrect.  Anybody using the fish_eye data will need to know the correct equation.  Library on github should be updated with the necessary code added to this function in rsutil.h.   

